Qi + alimentatia
The Core Idea: Food is Fuel for Your "Qi Factory"
In TCM, the primary function of eating is to create Qi (vital energy) and Xue (Blood). The quality of the food you eat directly determines the quality of the energy and substance your body can produce.
The "engine room" for this process is the Spleen and Stomach system.
The Stomach (Wei) is the "receiving dock." It takes in food and begins to "rot and ripen" it.
The Spleen (Pi) is the "factory manager." It transforms the food from the Stomach into Gu Qi (Food Qi), a refined, usable energy, and then transports this Qi throughout the body.
If this factory is weak or given poor quality raw materials, the entire system suffers.
 The Two Main Classifications of Food
To understand how to fuel the factory, TCM classifies all foods based on two key properties:
1. Nature (æ€§, XÃ¬ng): The food's thermal effect on the body.
Hot (çƒ­, RÃ¨): Warming, stimulating. (e.g., lamb, chili peppers).
Warm (æ¸©, WÄ“n): Gently warming. (e.g., chicken, ginger, onions).
Neutral (å¹³, PÃ­ng): Balanced; neither warming nor cooling. (e.g., rice, carrots, most fish).
Cool (å‡‰, LiÃ¡ng): Gently cooling. (e.g., mint, cucumber, apple).
Cold (å¯’, HÃ¡n): Very cooling. (e.g., watermelon, seaweed, tofu).
2. Flavor (å‘³, WÃ¨i): The food's action and affinity for certain organs.
Sweet (ç”˜, GÄn): Tonifies, harmonizes, moistens. Affinity for Spleen/Stomach.
Sour (é…¸, SuÄn): Astringes, prevents leakage. Affinity for Liver.
Bitter (è‹¦, KÇ”): Dries, drains, clears heat. Affinity for Heart.
Pungent/Acrid (è¾›, XÄ«n): Disperses, circulates Qi and Blood. Affinity for Lungs.
Salty (å’¸, XiÃ¡n): Softens, purges, descends. Affinity for Kidneys.

 Key Implications: A Summary of How to Eat for Qi
Based on this system, here are the main principles for using diet to manage your Qi:
1. Eat for Your Constitution: This is personalized medicine.
If you have a "Cold" condition (e.g., feel cold, low energy, pale tongue), you should eat more Warm/Hot foods to add Yang and fire up your factory.
If you have a "Hot" condition (e.g., feel hot, red face, thirst), you should eat more Cool/Cold foods to cool you down and conserve Yin.
2. Eat with the Seasons: This is living in harmony with the Tao.
Spring/Summer: Nature provides cooling foods (leafy greens, fruits) to balance the external heat.
Autumn/Winter: Nature provides warming foods (root vegetables, squash, meats) to help us stay warm and conserve energy.
3. Balance is Everything: Don't overdo one flavor or nature. Too much sweet food damages the Spleen. Too much spicy food can dry up your fluids. A varied diet ensures a balanced system.
4. Protect Your "Factory" (The Spleen): The most important principle.
The Spleen hates Cold and Dampness. Therefore, eating too many raw, cold, or icy foods and drinks directly weakens your main energy-producing organ.
Warm, cooked foods are generally easier to digest and put less strain on the Spleen, allowing it to produce high-quality Qi efficiently.
In short, TCM sees diet not as a rigid set of rules, but as a dynamic, intelligent way to provide your body with the highest quality fuel possible, so your "Qi factory" can run smoothly for a long, healthy life.
